<font color="#FF0000">BE PROUD</font><br>
<tt>Thu May 29 20:01:50 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Do not dirty your hands with responses to sick and guilty draft dodgers like Spatz.  If he was anything of a doctor, and truly informed on historical affairs, he would know that from almost any rational point of view, the war we fought in vietnam was not in vain.  <br><br>
Behind the shield of the U.S. presence in Vietnam most of S.E. Asia united and became prosperous by forming and participating in ASEAN, the Association of S.E. Asian nations.  Look at the economies of Thailand, the Philippenes, Malaysia and the other ASEAN countries and you will find a solid block of democratic countries with market economies.  This could not have been done without the U.S. effort in Vietnam and anyone familiar with their history and their press knows that.  <br><br>
Moreover, the enormous drain on the economy of the former Soviet Union in support of their client state N. Vietnam hastened the collapse of that evil empire.  Twenty years ago, just after the US had been militarily defeated in Vietnam, nearly 60% of the world was communist.  Now only a very small fraction of that percentage makes that claim.  Even Vietnam is moving toward a market economy which cannot resist the eventual pressures of democracy.  It is possible in our lifetime that we will see democratic elections held in Vietnam.  <br><br>
As a result of your efforts and sacrifices, my brothers and sisters, your children are the first generation to grow up in a world moving toward democracy.  The nuclear threat that hung over us since WWII is largely gone.  Vietnam was a major contribution to that, and you should be proud.<br><br>
So ignore the Spatz's, the Clinton's, the Fonda's.  Let them wallow in the filth of their own cowardice and self-serving ignorance.  Don't dignify their swinish wails of anxiety with replies.  Be proud!
<p><code>-- Otto@mce.com  (Otto Lehrack, U.S. Marine) </code><p>


